Well, my internet's been on the fritz lately. Ugh. Damn comcast.&nbsp;It explains my lack of updates&nbsp;about my brother's wedding. Yes, he got married.&nbsp;Yes, I caught the bouquet.&nbsp;

Anyway, my malfunctioning internet hasn't prevented me from shopping online. Today I managed to spend money. I bought the PSP version of Tales of Destiny 2. Yes, I know it's in Japanese. Ugh, I'm&nbsp;hoping that won't prevent me from enjoying the game&nbsp;completely. I do believe there are online guides to...well...guide me.

So, hopefully this will play out well.&nbsp;

Watched all of Tenpou Ibun Ayakashi Ayashi today.&nbsp;I'd had the thing for a while, just never sat&nbsp;down to watch it. It was a pretty interesting series. The idea of wanting to leave this world for another struck me pretty hard. I'd always felt out of place among people, distanced myself from them. "I'm not like them; I&nbsp;can't be like them". Maybe it's true, maybe it's not. I&nbsp;don't know. Maybe my thoughts and feelings have taken form in a sense just like the youi and changed me into something from which I can't return. Maybe it's a good thing, maybe a bad thing.&nbsp;I can't tell.

We're all humans living on this world; there is no difference between us.

Maybe that's the case, but I refuse to believe it. Everything else I've ever known has told me to&nbsp;fight against the inevitable, and in this case the inevitable was that&nbsp;I am forced to live only in this world. This was the first series I'd ever seen that was so fatalistic. It is utterly&nbsp;impossible for me to believe now that this is the only way things could be, that this is the only choice. I've chosen this path to find a world that I can exist in, and I have acknowledged that this is not the one. Perception creates the world; without it, there would be no defined "reality". Hell, all reality is is what the majority of people agree this world should be.

But this world is not the&nbsp;end. I know it.&nbsp;

I have heard something stirring at its core: something I cannot even put into words.

Just like the characters in the story, I have seen the other world&nbsp;and can no longer be satisfied with this one. Or, put more accurately, I no longer have to "just put up" with this one.

This thing...I seek it, I chase it more than any other thing in this life. I want to clasp it in my hands, embrace it, understand it. Whatever it is, even the slightest taste I've had of it fulfills me more than anything in this world ever could. And its filled, somehow, with the feeling of regret. Whether regret that I did not come to know this sooner, or regret that I came to know it at all, I cannot tell.

I have said once before that I would turn my back on this world. Of that, I am now certain more than ever. My path is out there, to chase that world I once had seen. And I know that it is not a crime to want to return there because I'm not returning because it would be an easier life, or because I want to run away from this world but, perhaps, because it is my dream to find it--the place I am to go to next.&nbsp;

I feel as Drosselmeyer must have felt. "This story is over; it's time to move on to the next one". I feel as though I've accomplished here what I must, and that it is yet again time to move on to whatever is next in pursuit of that other world.&nbsp;

I realize now that i'vee always been in search of an other, whether it was another person or another world, it just depended on the time of&nbsp; my life. I'm not searching for a reason to exist; I'm just searching for a place. The never-ending search for that place--that is the meaning of my existence.

Yes, I know, Princess Tutu is a weird name for a series, and it probably sounds all girly and stupid. At first, I thought it was, but once I hit the end of season one, I realized that there was so much more to the series. Of course, the part that is relevant to this entry is the second half which deals mostly with authors and the responsibilities to their characters.

Man, after surviving Nano, I can totally understand the&nbsp;author's problem of having characters mutiny on you, or&nbsp;having your characters remain stubbornly silent.&nbsp;When I don't find myself crying over this series, I find myself laughing over how they incorporate the normal problems of authors into this story about stories.

At any rate, a short rambling entry, but that's all&nbsp;I can manage at this time. I've got a story to finish.&nbsp;

