So, there seems to be some interesting TV shows this season: 1 for almost every day of the week. My scehdule (aside from school stuff) goes something like this:

Monday: Aliens in America (CW at 8&nbsp;o'clock)
Tuesday: House (Fox at 9 o'clock ^^)
Wednesday: Pushing Daisies (ABC at 8&nbsp;o'clock)

I was surprised by Pushing Daisies.&nbsp;As it turned out, I really liked it despite its, somewhat strange premise. Well, maybe I liked it because of that, its fairytale feel and its just devastating cuteness.&nbsp;

The basic premise was that there was this guy who could bring&nbsp;dead things (and people) back to life&nbsp;if he touched them once, but would kill them if he touched them again after bringing them back. Also, if he didn't re-kill them again within a minute of bringing them back to life, someone in close proximity to them (excluding&nbsp;him, I assume) would die in the original person's place. So, as the story goes, there was this girl he was&nbsp;in love with when he was a kid and he finds out she was murdered. So, he was working with a detective to solve homicide cases by bringing the victim back to life and asking what happened to them) and he ended up bringing her back. Problem was, he didn't kill her again.

As the story goes, the two fell in love (bringing her back to life helped her opinion of him alot I guess) but they can't ever touch or she'd die again.

It's a really sad story, but it's done with this wonderful touch of the absurd, giving the show an overall nice&nbsp;feel.&nbsp;

I'm really happy with this one. I'll probably keep watching it for a while. Now I just need something on&nbsp;Thursday and Friday and I'm good to go! ^^&nbsp;

OMG! I got ahold of the first five episodes of the Romeo X Juliet series and OMG! I'm totally hooked! I mean, yeah, I know I'm probably setting myself up to be miserable when I see the end of the series--the thing's already killing me with the angst anyway--but I can't resist!! Ah, Romeo's precious--utterly useless, but precious nonetheless and Juliet just totally kicks ass (when she's not moping around over Romeo that is).&nbsp; 

I really like the changes made for the series. The cast includes characters from lots of different Shakespeare plays as well as a carciature of Shakespeare himself and of course, there's lots of references to the various plays!! I also adore the ryoumas (pegasi basically)! They're sooo freaking awesome! There are alot of changes but much has stayed the same. I think I'm gonna really like this show even if the ending turns out to be sad. 

Of course, I'm still holding out hope for a happy ending, but I know how unlikely that is for this particular story. But, if the ending must be sad, if they must both die I hope it's not in a silly way like in the play. Their deaths in the play were so senseless, and, I suppose that's part of the tragedy, because it was so preventable. But still, if these characters must die, I want their deaths to be meaningful. I also hope that if the writers chose to keep the ending as a tragedy that the two can still die together. I believe that it's cruel to keep one of them alive after the other has died. Is that wrong? I dunno. I guess I'm just kinda getting all bent out of shape about the ending cause I keep aniticipating it as being sad. 

In any case, whatever the ending will be, I'm still gonna hope that it can be happy for both of them. 

Sigh. I'm hopelessly optimistic.&nbsp;

Much to my dismay, I find myself becoming more and more impulsive (especially when it comes to spending money *sigh*). I mean, I never though of myself as impulsive before. Before, I used to think and think...and, well, not do much else. Still, I'm not certain that this change is for the best. After all, I might end up broke because of it....^^;

But I must admit that being impulsive has served me well in some regards. I mean, I didn't have to really think about any decisions. I would just make my choice on a whim and that would be that. I mean, that's how I ended up at UF in the first place I guess.

But now, I feel I can't be impulsive not only about my choice of grad school, but also, whether or not my chosen path is still right for me.&nbsp;

To tell the truth, I feel as though I'm about to make some kind of colossal mistake that will cause my world to collapse in on me no matter *which* school I choose. I guess the reason I've become so impulsive is so I can avoid making decisions. But, regardless of what decision I make and whether or not I make it on a whim,&nbsp; I will have to live with the consequences.

I've been following an unseen path blindly, and I have never known where I was going.

All I know is that I dislike uncertainty.
